<subSubSection pageId="88" pageNumber="89" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="88.[151,1437,690,2013]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,942,968]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Surface spinules fully covering cells m 
<subScript attach="left" box="[762,770,961,975]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">1</subScript>
, m 
<subScript attach="left" box="[805,813,961,975]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">2</subScript>
, and cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[900,908,961,975]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">1</subScript>
(sometimes restricted to radular areas). Paramere, in lateral view, clavate, strongly expanded apically; anterior margin expanding dorsally and anteriorly in apical third; apex strongly indented in anterior third, with sclerotised ridge in posterior half; in dorsal view, sclerotised ridge slightly sinuous, bearing posterior tooth. Aedeagus complex unipartite; in lateral view, ventral process with apical expansion larger than dorsal lobe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="89" lastPageNumber="90" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="88.[151,1437,690,2013]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1122,1148]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Description.</emphasis>
Colouration. Body with white striped-pattern; variation: vertex with stripe along posterior margin weak when present; mesopraescutum with lateral stripes fused to lateral spots on posterior margin; metascutellum almost entirely lighter than rest of thorax; mesoepisternum with markings usually inconspicuous; older specimens with markings with dark outline. Head and thorax pale yellow, yellowish-orange, yellowish-brown; genal process slightly lighter than head. Eye grey to dark red; ocelli colourless to orange. Antenna light yellowish-brown, segments 1–2 concolorous with head. Clypeus concolorous with head, slightly lighter medially and slightly darker along edges; rostrum light yellow. Thorax with margins of sclerites slightly darker. Forewing colourless to yellowish, yellow around Cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[398,414,1393,1407]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">1b</subScript>
and sometimes slightly around M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[796,822,1393,1407]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">1+2</subScript>
, M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[861,886,1393,1407]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">3+4</subScript>
and Cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[973,988,1393,1407]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">1a</subScript>
; veins yellow; pterostigma concolorous or slightly lighter than veins. Hindwing colourless. Fore- and midleg dark yellow, hindleg light yellow. Abdomen light straw-coloured, pale yellow to light yellowish-brown; intersegmental membranes light straw-coloured; spiracular sclerites concolorous with tergites. Male terminalia irregularly light to dark yellow. Female terminalia irregularly light to dark yellow, proctiger darker apically.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="88.[151,1437,690,2013]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
Structure. Body length ♁ 
<quantity box="[483,617,1554,1581]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" unit="mm" value="2.35" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="2.2">2.2–2.5 mm</quantity>
(2.35± 
<quantity box="[696,784,1554,1581]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.1 mm</quantity>
), 
<specimenCount box="[802,823,1555,1581]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
<quantity box="[829,962,1555,1581]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.45" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="2.3" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" unit="mm" value="2.45" valueMax="2.6" valueMin="2.3">2.3–2.6 mm</quantity>
(2.48± 
<quantity box="[1040,1141,1555,1581]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" unit="mm" value="0.13">0.13 mm</quantity>
) (5 ♁, 
<specimenCount box="[1217,1257,1554,1581]" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" type="female">5 ♀</specimenCount>
). Genal process (
<figureCitation box="[160,257,1591,1618]" captionStart="FIGURES 148–162" captionStartId="43.[151,264,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1797]" captionTargetId="figure-22@43.[151,1436,181,1797]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURES 148–162. Mitrapsylla spp., head, dorsal view: 148. M. holocalycis sp. nov.; 149. M. itacoatiara sp. nov.; 150. M. itaparica (Crawford); 151. M. machaerii sp. nov.; 152. M. melanothorax sp. nov.; 153. M. ochra sp. nov.; 154. M. pallida sp. nov.; 155. M. periandrae sp. nov.; 156. M. pterodontis sp. nov.; 157. M. pterogynis sp. nov.; 158. M. securigera sp. nov.; 159. M. soror sp. nov.; 160. M. truncata sp. nov.; 161. M. villosi sp. nov.; 162. M. xanthoptera sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4297611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4297611/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Fig. 161</figureCitation>
) expanded or subconical, irregularly narrowing towards acute, subacute or narrowly rounded apex, 0.6 times as long as vertex along midline. Antenna 2.2–2.5 times as long as head width; longest terminal seta about as long as segment 10. Apical labium segment 0.2 times longer than head width and 0.7–0.8 times longer than median segment. Forewing (
<figureCitation box="[380,475,1699,1725]" captionStart="FIGURES 183–192" captionStartId="46.[151,264,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1797]" captionTargetId="figure-21@46.[151,1436,181,1797]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURES 183–192. Mitrapsylla spp., forewing: 183. M. ochra sp. nov.; 184. M. pallida sp. nov.; 185. M. periandrae sp. nov.; 186. M. pterodontis sp. nov.; 187. M. pterogynis sp. nov.; 188. M. securigera sp. nov.; 189. M. soror sp. nov.; 190. M. truncata sp. nov.; 191. M. villosi sp. nov.; 192. M. xanthoptera sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4297617" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4297617/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Fig. 191</figureCitation>
) 2.8–2.9 times as long as head width, 2.3 times as long as wide, obovoid, slightly narrowly or broadly rounded apically; vein M+Cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[685,693,1753,1767]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">1</subScript>
0.3–0.4 times as long as Cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1016,1024,1753,1767]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">1</subScript>
; ratio a/b 1.4–1.7; ratio c/d 0.7–0.8; ratio e/f 0.5–1.0. Surface spinules distinctly (
<figureCitation box="[665,748,1771,1797]" captionStart="FIGURES 38–43" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1967,1991]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,1340,1942]" captionTargetId="figure-137@14.[190,1398,1340,1943]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 38–43. Mitrapsylla spp., forewing surface spinules: 38. M. cassiae sp. nov.; 39. M. securigera sp. nov.; 40. M. pterogynis sp. nov.; 41. M. aurantia sp. nov.; 42. M. itaparica (Crawford); 43. M. pallida sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4297593" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4297593/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
) to moderately (
<figureCitation box="[938,1021,1771,1797]" captionStart="FIGURES 38–43" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1967,1991]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,1340,1942]" captionTargetId="figure-137@14.[190,1398,1340,1943]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 38–43. Mitrapsylla spp., forewing surface spinules: 38. M. cassiae sp. nov.; 39. M. securigera sp. nov.; 40. M. pterogynis sp. nov.; 41. M. aurantia sp. nov.; 42. M. itaparica (Crawford); 43. M. pallida sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4297593" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4297593/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
) spaced, forming rhomboids; covering apical half of cell r 
<subScript attach="left" box="[409,417,1825,1839]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">1</subScript>
, apical half or third of cell r 
<subScript attach="left" box="[738,746,1825,1839]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">2</subScript>
, fully covering cells m 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1008,1016,1825,1839]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">1</subScript>
, m 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1052,1060,1825,1839]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">2</subScript>
, and cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1150,1158,1825,1839]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">1</subScript>
(sometimes restricted to radular areas), m 
<subScript attach="left" box="[341,349,1861,1875]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">2</subScript>
basally, and most of cell cu 
<subScript attach="right" box="[664,672,1861,1875]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">2</subScript>
; leaving spinule-free spaces along veins (
<figureCitation box="[1144,1228,1843,1869]" captionStart="FIGURES 38–43" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1967,1991]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,1340,1942]" captionTargetId="figure-137@14.[190,1398,1340,1943]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 38–43. Mitrapsylla spp., forewing surface spinules: 38. M. cassiae sp. nov.; 39. M. securigera sp. nov.; 40. M. pterogynis sp. nov.; 41. M. aurantia sp. nov.; 42. M. itaparica (Crawford); 43. M. pallida sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.02 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4297593" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4297593/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
). Radular spinules sometimes present in r 
<subScript attach="left" box="[404,412,1897,1911]" fontSize="6" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">2</subScript>
but inconspicuous. Metatibia 0.6–0.8 times as long as head width.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="88.[151,1437,690,2013]" lastBlockId="89.[151,1437,151,1042]" lastPageId="89" lastPageNumber="90" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">
Terminalia. Male. Proctiger, in lateral view, 0.4 times as long as head width; with long, weakly tapered, weakly down-curved posterior lobe. Paramere, in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[777,877,1951,1977]" captionStart="FIGURES 274–282" captionStartId="56.[151,264,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,182,1797]" captionTargetId="figure-21@56.[151,1436,181,1797]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURES 274–282. Mitrapsylla spp., male terminalia, lateral view: 274, 277, 280: paramere, outer surface; 275, 278, 281: paramere, inner surface; 276, 279, 282: distal segment of aedeagus. 274‾276. M. truncata sp. nov.; 277‾279. M. villosi sp. nov.; 280‾282. M. xanthoptera sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4297638" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4297638/files/figure.png" pageId="88" pageNumber="89">Figs 277</figureCitation>
‾279) 0.7–0.8 times as long as proctiger; clavate, strongly expanded apically; anterior margin expanding dorsally and anteriorly in apical third, irregularly concave basally; posterior margin strongly expanding in apical third or quarter, slightly concave subapically, weakly convex in basal half; apex strongly indented in anterior third, with sclerotised ridge in posterior half (
<figureCitation box="[1176,1273,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 274–282" captionStartId="56.[151,264,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,182,1797]" captionTargetId="figure-21@56.[151,1436,181,1797]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURES 274–282. Mitrapsylla spp., male terminalia, lateral view: 274, 277, 280: paramere, outer surface; 275, 278, 281: paramere, inner surface; 276, 279, 282: distal segment of aedeagus. 274‾276. M. truncata sp. nov.; 277‾279. M. villosi sp. nov.; 280‾282. M. xanthoptera sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4297638" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4297638/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 278</figureCitation>
); inner surface (
<figureCitation box="[160,255,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 274–282" captionStartId="56.[151,264,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,182,1797]" captionTargetId="figure-21@56.[151,1436,181,1797]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURES 274–282. Mitrapsylla spp., male terminalia, lateral view: 274, 277, 280: paramere, outer surface; 275, 278, 281: paramere, inner surface; 276, 279, 282: distal segment of aedeagus. 274‾276. M. truncata sp. nov.; 277‾279. M. villosi sp. nov.; 280‾282. M. xanthoptera sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4297638" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4297638/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 278</figureCitation>
) covered with short setae, longer basally and along posterior margin, with row of thick setae along apical anterior margin, several thick setae below sclerotised ridge, and group of stout setae on apical posterior margin; in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[328,425,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 283–312" captionStartId="57.[151,264,1740,1764]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1717]" captionTargetId="figure-22@57.[151,1436,181,1717]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURES 283–312. Mitrapsylla spp., parameres, dorsal view: 283. M. aeschynomenis sp. nov.; 284. M. amazonica sp. nov.; 285. M. andirae sp. nov.; 286. M. aurantia sp. nov., 287. M. brevigenis sp. nov.; 288. M. cassiae sp. nov.; 289. M. ceplaciensis (White &amp; Hodkinson); 290. M. clavata sp. nov.; 291. M. cubana Crawford; 292. M. cujabensis sp. nov.; 293. M. cuspidata sp. nov.; 294. M. didyma sp. nov.; 295. M. domahovskii sp. nov.; 296. M. halbertae sp. nov.; 297. M. hamata sp. nov.; 298. M. holocalycis sp. nov.; 299. M. itacoatiara sp. nov.; 300. M. itaparica (Crawford); 301. M. machaerii sp. nov.; 302. M. melanothorax sp. nov.; 303. M. ochra sp. nov.; 304. M. pallida sp. nov.; 305. M. periandrae sp. nov.; 306. M. pterodontis sp. nov.; 307. M. pterogynis sp. nov.; 308. M. securigera sp. nov.; 309. M. soror sp. nov.; 310. M. truncata sp. nov.; 311. M. villosi sp. nov.; 312. M. xanthoptera sp. nov. Anterior part up." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4297640" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4297640/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 311</figureCitation>
), sclerotised ridge slightly sinuous, bearing posterior tooth. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[1228,1325,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 274–282" captionStartId="56.[151,264,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,182,1797]" captionTargetId="figure-21@56.[151,1436,181,1797]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURES 274–282. Mitrapsylla spp., male terminalia, lateral view: 274, 277, 280: paramere, outer surface; 275, 278, 281: paramere, inner surface; 276, 279, 282: distal segment of aedeagus. 274‾276. M. truncata sp. nov.; 277‾279. M. villosi sp. nov.; 280‾282. M. xanthoptera sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4297638" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4297638/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 279</figureCitation>
) complex unipartite; in lateral view, dorsal lobe subtriangular; ventral process weakly to strongly upturned, with apical expansion larger than dorsal lobe, irregularly oval, slightly angulate at apex, bearing long, conical tubercle.—Female (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 337–342" captionStartId="62.[151,264,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,184,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-21@62.[151,1436,181,1797]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 337–342. Mitrapsylla spp., female terminalia, lateral view: 337. M. pterogynis sp. nov.; 338. M. securigera sp. nov.; 339. M. soror sp. nov.; 340. M. truncata sp. nov.; 341. M. villosi sp. nov.; 342. M. xanthoptera sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4297650" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4297650/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 341</figureCitation>
). Proctiger, in lateral view, 0.9 times as long as head width; dorsal outline moderately to strongly concave distal to circumanal ring, apical extension sinuous, apex slightly to moderately upturned, smoothly transversally truncate to strongly obliquely truncate; circumanal ring 0.3 times as long as proctiger. Subgenital plate, in lateral view, 0.5–0.6 times as long as proctiger; apex well-developed; basal half of ventral outline strongly expanded, apical half almost straight to slightly convex; covered with medium long setae in median third and ventrally throughout, short setae in apical third, long setae at apex, and group of long setae on dorsum subapically, with seta-free patch subapically; in ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[405,502,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 363–372" captionStartId="64.[151,264,1003,1027]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,198,975]" captionTargetId="figure-21@64.[151,1436,181,979]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURES 363–372. Mitrapsylla spp., female subgenital plate, ventral view: 363. M. ochra sp. nov.; 364. M. pallida sp. nov.; 365. M. periandrae sp. nov.; 366. M. pterodontis sp. nov.; 367. M. pterogynis sp. nov.; 368. M. securigera sp. nov.; 369. M. soror sp. nov.; 370. M. truncata sp. nov.; 371. M. villosi sp. nov.; 372. M. xanthoptera sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4297654" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4297654/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 371</figureCitation>
), lateral margins evenly, strongly narrowing at apical third towards narrow, acutely rounded apex.
</paragraph>
